The paper deals with the computational complexity of two important similarity measures between sequences, namely the longest common subsequence (LCS) and the dynamic time warping distance (DTWD). These measures are central to a variety of applications in computer science, including data mining, bioinformatics, and pattern recognition. The paper shows that computing the LCS or the DTWD of two sequences of length n over a constant size alphabet in O(n^(2-epsilon)) time, for some epsilon > 0, refutes the popular Strong Exponential Time Hypothesis (SETH). This suggests that the paper belongs to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category, which deals with the design and analysis of efficient algorithms and data structures. Additionally, the paper may also belong to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category, which deals with the study of the inherent difficulty of computational problems, and the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category, which deals with the design and analysis of algorithms for geometric problems. The paper also discusses the time complexity of approximating the DTWD of two strings in truly subquadratic time, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category, which deals with the mathematical foundations of computer science.
